<para id="para-00007">Identifying each component of a PICOT question is necessary to formulate a clearly defined problem. This question will then guide the literature search and the steps in EBDM in public health. As previously noted, the population may include individuals, communities, or a larger population group. From those categories, the nurse must decide if the population will be further refined, such by age, literacy level, or socioeconomic status. Interventions may be a specific change or treatment but may also be viewed under an approach to health not previously used or studied in this specific population with the outlined concern. The comparison may be a different intervention, often the one currently in practice, or the absence of the proposed intervention. Outcomes will contain measurable results or the aftermath of the implemented intervention. Time outlines how long the intervention will be in place and/or how long outcomes will be measured. <link target-id="table-00002" document="m00155"/> provides example PICOT questions as well as the breakdown of the elements for each question.</para>
