<para id="para-00031">McMaster University’s Health Evidence website offers tools for evidence-informed decision-making. Examples of tools include an EIDM checklist, a resource to guide, a search tracker, and search strategies for developing a PICOT. Watch the video about using their resources. Then answer the following questions:</para>
<list list-type="enumerated" number-style="arabic" id="list-00007">
<item>What are the three main methods for searching within Health Evidence?</item>
<item>Health Evidence is an online database that utilizes sources at which level of evidence to evaluate the effectives of public health interventions? Why is this evidence leveling important?</item>
<item>Articles in this database are critically appraised and rated for quality. What rating system is used in this database?</item>
</list>
</note>
<para id="para-00032">By utilizing these tools, nurses and other health care providers can make the complex process of EBDM more attainable by breaking these steps into manageable tasks.</para>
</section>
<section class="chapter-summary" id="sect-00012">
  <title>Chapter Summary</title>
<para id="para-00033">Evidence-based practice and evidence-based decision-making are key resources to help accomplish health care goals. Evidence-based decision-making in public health is outlined by seven steps: define, search, appraise, synthesize, adapt, implement, and evaluate. The EBDM process allows for a more objective decision-making method. The first step, defining the problem, usually formatted as a PICOT question, leads the way for the rest of the process. Often, interventions outlined in research may not fit with the designated community and require adaptation. The NCCMT’s Model for evidence-based decision-making assists with this process.</para>
</section>
